  abstract = {The Pierre Auger Observatory, located in western Argentina, is the world's largest cosmic-ray observatory. While it was originally built to study the cosmic-ray flux above \$10\textasciicircum\{18.5\}\textasciitilde\$eV, several enhancements have reduced this energy threshold. One such enhancement is a surface array composed of a triangular grid of \$19\$ water-Cherenkov detectors separated by \$433\textasciitilde\$m (SD-433) to explore the energies down to about \$10\textasciicircum\{16\}\textasciitilde\$eV. We are developing two research lines employing the SD-433. Firstly, we will measure the energy spectrum in a region where previous experiments have shown evidence of the second knee. Secondly, we will search for ultra-high energy photons to study PeV cosmic-ray sources residing in the Galactic center. In this work, we introduce the SD-433 and we show that it is fully efficient above \$5\textbackslash times 10\textasciicircum\{16\}\textasciitilde\$eV for hadronic primaries with \$\textbackslash theta {$<$} 45\textasciicircum\textbackslash circ\$. Using seven years of data, we present the parametrization of the lateral distribution function of measured signals. Finally, we show that an angular resolution of \$1.8\textasciicircum\textbackslash circ\$ (\$0.5\textasciicircum\textbackslash circ\$) can be attained at the lowest (highest) primary energies. Our study lays the goundmark for measurements in the energy range above \$10\textasciicircum\{16\}\textasciitilde\$eV by utilizing the SD-433 and thus expanding the scientific output of the Auger surface detector.},
